<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900809-0050</DOCNO><DOCID>900809-0050.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>07/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   GORBACHEV GAVE himself two years to improve the SovietUnion's economy.   On the third day of a Communist Party congress, the Sovietpresident and party leader told a TV reporter, &quot;I think thatin two years, if there are no changes, this leadership mustgo.&quot; It was the first time he set a deadline for turningaround the country's economic and social problems. Contraryto some expectations, the congress hasn't turned into anall-out attack on Gorbachev, though both he and his Politburocolleagues have taken sharp criticism. Instead, moderates andhard-liners are engaged in a painful search for ways toensure the future existence of the party.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We need to retain socialism, but how?&quot; asked one delegatefrom the Ukraine. &quot;Stalin built his model. Now we don't likethat, but we have no new model. We're in an ideologicalcrisis.&quot;   ---   Secretary of State Baker proposed that 24 Western nationsestablish a Central American aid program to help &quot;broaden thesupport for democracy and development.&quot; Several countriessaid they would consider the idea. The proposal came as thetwo dozen countries agreed to offer aid to four EasternEuropean nations.   ---   Albania's officials stated they would meet with arepresentative of foreign embassies sheltering over 200Albanian asylum-seekers in Tirana, the capital. In Vienna,diplomats said embassies were told that people seeking toleave would get passports. Mobs had stormed the embassies bycrashing trucks through gates or scaling walls.   ---   Iran's president said his nation had moved closer to peacewith Iraq over the past few months. Rafsanjani remarked thathe felt &quot;the atmosphere between the two countries hasimproved.&quot; On Tuesday, Iranian and Iraqi foreign ministersheld their first direct meeting since an August 1988cease-fire that ended an eight-year war.   ---   Bush plans to propose, at a NATO summit opening today inLondon, that Soviet leader Gorbachev be invited to addressthe Western military alliance, according to diplomaticsources. The U.S. also is recommending that Moscow and theWarsaw Pact be allowed to send permanent observers to NATOheadquarters.   ---   Thatcher welcomed Mandela to London, three years after shedenounced the African National Congress as a terroristorganization. The British prime minister and South Africanblack nationalist leader called their three-hour meeting asuccess despite disagreement about economic sanctions and theANC's commitment to armed struggle.   ---   East Germany agreed to Bonn's agenda for political unionby proposing Dec. 2 for the first free vote in a unitedGermany since 1932, preparing the way for talks to formallyend German division. West Germans viewed the accord as a signthat East Berlin's leadership has overcome internalopposition to swift unification.   ---   Studies found that aging men and cancer patients canbenefit from hormonal treatments. The increase in fat tissueand muscular atrophy seen in many elderly men can be reversedby injections of human growth hormone, one report said.Another study concluded that a sex hormone helped cancerpatients gain weight.   ---   A government panel blamed the pilot for a USAir crash atNew York's LaGuardia Airport last Sept. 20 that killed twopassengers. The National Transportation Safety Board said thecaptain failed to detect a rudder-control problem as hetaxied for takeoff, and then failed to correct the situationaggressively.   ---   Liberia's president met with U.S. Ambassador Peter de Vosin Monrovia as rebels tightened their grip on the capital.Washington officials said Doe declined an offer for help infleeing the city, which has been without electricity andwater for over a week.   ---   The Energy Department estimates the cost of cleaning upits nuclear-arms plants and other facilities soon could riseto $6 billion a year -- about twice as much as the currentlevel. The department said it could cost $31.6 billion fromfiscal 1992 through fiscal 1996 to remove, treat and storewaste from nearly 100 sites.   ---   The New Jersey Supreme Court ordered two PrincetonUniversity eating clubs to admit women as members. Thecourt's ruling came in an 11-year-old lawsuit filed by aformer Princeton student who claimed that the clubs'males-only policies discriminated against women.   ---   A constitutional crisis was defused in Taiwan as theruling Nationalist Party government and opposition leadersagreed on democratic changes, including a popular vote forpresident to end four decades of one-party domination. Underthe accord, native Taiwanese will be given more politicalpower.</TEXT></DOC>